Instructions: Step 1

Gather data, determine the method of data collection and provenance of the data (3 points)

In the earliest phase, select a data source and problem. Feel free to share and discuss your idea on the class discussion board.

AllLife Bank wants to focus on its credit card customer base in the next financial year. They have been advised by their marketing research team, that the penetration in the market can be improved. Based on this input, the Marketing team proposes to run personalised campaigns to target new customers as well as upsell to existing customers. Another insight from the market research was that the customers perceive the support services of the back poorly. Based on this, the Operations team wants to upgrade the service delivery model, to ensure that customers queries are resolved faster. Head of Marketing and Head of Delivery both decide to reach out to the Data Science team for help.

Data Source : https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/eyowakim/credit-card-customer-data

Data Description : Data is of various customers of a bank with their credit limit, the total number of credit cards the customer has, and different channels through which customer has contacted the bank for any queries, different channels include visiting the bank, online and through a call centre.

  1. SL_No : Serial Number
  2. Customer Key - Customer Idenfification Number
  3. Avg_Credit_Limit - Average Credit Card limit for each customer
  4. Total_Credit_Cards - Total number of credit cards by customer
  5. Total_Visits_Bank - Total number of visits that customer made (yearly) personally to the bank
  6. Total_Visits_online - Total number of visits or online logins made by the customer (yearly)
  7. Total_calls_made - Total number of calls made by the customer to the bank or its customer service department (yearly)

Problem Approach¶

As the Data Science team, the first step would be to understand the available data and define the problem statement. Some potential steps to address the marketing and operations challenges could include:

  • Analyzing customer data: By analyzing customer data, the team can identify patterns and trends in customer behavior, such as spending habits, usage of credit card features, and customer demographics. This analysis can help the marketing team to identify new customer segments to target with personalized campaigns, and can also help the operations team to understand where customers are experiencing the most issues.

  • Developing predictive models: The team can use machine learning techniques to develop predictive models that can forecast which customers are most likely to respond positively to a particular campaign or to upsell offers. This can help the marketing team to prioritize which customers to target with their campaigns, and can also help the operations team to predict which customers are most likely to have service issues.

  • Improving customer support: By analyzing customer support data, the team can identify which types of issues are most commonly reported by customers and develop solutions to address those issues. For example, the team can develop chatbots or other automated systems that can quickly resolve common customer queries, freeing up human support staff to focus on more complex issues.

  • Monitoring campaign and support effectiveness: The team can track the effectiveness of marketing campaigns and customer support initiatives over time by analyzing key performance metrics such as customer satisfaction scores, customer retention rates, and credit card usage rates. This analysis can help the marketing and operations teams to continuously improve their strategies and tactics.

Using K-Means Clustering¶

K-Means clustering is an unsupervised learning algorithm that partitions data points into K clusters based on similarity. The algorithm works by iteratively assigning data points to their nearest cluster centroid and then recalculating the centroids based on the new assignments.

We will also use elbow method technique to determine optimal number of clusters to use in K-Means clustering. In involves plotting the within-cluster sum of squares for different values of K and selecting the value of K where the decrease of sum of the squares began to level off.

We will use Silhouette score to evaluate the quality of clustering results for different valutes of K. A higher Silhouette score for a particular value of K indicates that the clustering is more appropriate for the given data.

In [54]:
clusters=range(1,9)
meanDistortions=[]

for k in clusters:
    model=KMeans(n_clusters=k)
    model.fit(subset_scaled_df)
    prediction=model.predict(subset_scaled_df)
    distortion=sum(np.min(cdist(subset_scaled_df, model.cluster_centers_, 'euclidean'), axis=1)) / subset_scaled_df.shape[0]
                           
    meanDistortions.append(distortion)

    print('Number of Clusters:', k, '\tAverage Distortion:', distortion)

plt.plot(clusters, meanDistortions, 'bx-')
plt.xlabel('k')
plt.ylabel('Average Distortion')
plt.title('Selecting k with the Elbow Method', fontsize=20)

The elbow point is the point on the graph where the rate of decrease in the average distortion (WCSS) starts to slow down, indicating that adding more clusters doesn't provide much additional benefit in reducing the distortion. Therefore, the optimal number of clusters is typically chosen to be the number of clusters at the elbow point.

Observation The appropriate value of K from elbow curve above seems to be 3 or 4.

The Silhouette score can be used to evaluate the quality of the clustering results for different values of K (the number of clusters). A higher Silhouette score for a particular value of K indicates that the clustering is more appropriate for the given dat.

From silhoutte score, it seems 3 is good value of K.

The Silhouette scores are calculated for each data point and represent how well the data point fits into its assigned cluster. A higher Silhouette score indicates a better fit.

The visualizer displays a graph where each data point is represented as a horizontal bar, with the length of the bar indicating the Silhouette score for that data point. The bars are grouped by cluster and are sorted in descending order by Silhouette score. The dashed line in the graph represents the average Silhouette score across all data points.

By examining the graph, we can identify the number of clusters that maximizes the average Silhouette score and indicates the best clustering solution for the given data.

Using Hierarchical Clustering¶

We will first evaluate multiple combinations of distance metrics and linkage methods to determine optimal approach to hierarchical clustering. We will use cophenet index to evaluate the quality of hierarchical clustering.

First we will identify distance metrics (euclidean, mahalanobis etc) and linkage methods. We will loop over each combination of distance metric and linkage method, where where hierarchical clustering is applied to the dataset using that combination.

The cophenet function is used to calculate the cophenet correlation coefficient, which measures the correlation between the distance of points in feature space and distance on the dendrogram for the resulting clustering solution. A higher cophenet correlation coefficient indicates a better clustering solution.

The cophenet correlation coefficient is printed for each combination of distance metric and linkage method.

If the highest cophenet correlation coefficient seen so far is surpassed by the current combination of distance metric and linkage method, then the highest cophenet correlation coefficient and corresponding distance metric and linkage method are updated.

In [67]:
# cophenet index is a measure of the correlation between the distance of points in feature space and distance on dendrogram
# closer it is to 1, the better is the clustering
distance_metrics = [ 'euclidean','chebyshev','mahalanobis','cityblock']
linkage_methods = ['single', 'complete', 'average', 'weighted']
high_cophenet_corr = 0
high_dm_lm = [0,0]
for dm in distance_metrics:
    for lm in linkage_methods:
        Z = linkage(subset_scaled_df, metric=dm, method=lm)
        c, coph_dists = cophenet(Z , pdist(subset_scaled_df))
        print('Cophent correlation for distance metrics {} and linkahe method {} is {}'.format(dm,lm,c))
        if high_cophenet_corr < c:
            high_cophenet_corr = c
            high_dm_lm[0] = dm
            high_dm_lm[1] = lm

Cophent correlation for distance metrics euclidean and linkahe method single is 0.8788676940541079

linkage_methods = ['single', 'complete', 'average','median','ward', 'weighted']
high_cophenet_corr = 0
high_dm_lm = [0,0]

for lm in linkage_methods:
    Z = linkage(subset_scaled_df, metric='euclidean', method=lm)
    c, coph_dists = cophenet(Z , pdist(subset_scaled_df))
    print('Cophent correlation for distance metrics {} and linkahe method {} is {}'.format('euclidean',lm,c))
    if high_cophenet_corr < c:
        high_cophenet_corr = c
        high_dm_lm[0] = dm
        high_dm_lm[1] = lm

Visualize the clustering of the dataset using different linkage methods and determine the linkage method that results in the highest cophenetic correlation coefficient, indicating the best clustering solution for the given data. By comparing the cophenetic correlation coefficient across different linkage methods, we can identify the optimal approach for hierarchical clustering on this dataset. The dendrogram plot provides a visual representation of the clustering solution and can be useful in identifying natural clusters within the data.

In [82]:
# List of all linkage methods to check
methods = ['single',
           'average', 
           'complete',           'centroid',
           'ward',
          'weighted']

# Calculate the pairwise distance form the dataset to be used in the cophenetic correlation calculation
#pw_distance = pdist(credit_scaled)

# Create lists to save results of coph calculation
compare_cols = ['Linkage', 'Cophenetic Coefficient']
compare = []

# Create a subplot image
fig, axs = plt.subplots(len(methods), 1, figsize=(15, 30))

# Enumerate through the list of all methods above
# Get linkage, plot dendrogram, calculate cophenetic coefficient
for i, method in enumerate(methods):
    
    Z = linkage(subset_scaled_df, metric='euclidean', method=method)

    dendrogram(Z, ax=axs[i]);
    axs[i].set_title(f'Dendrogram ({method.capitalize()} Linkage)')
    coph_corr, coph_dist = cophenet(Z, pdist(subset_scaled_df))
    axs[i].annotate(f'Cophenetic\nCoefficient\n{coph_corr:0.2f}', 
                    (0.80, 0.80),
                    xycoords='axes fraction')
    compare.append([method, coph_corr])

Observations Dendrogram with average linkage method shows distinct and separate cluster

Insights

Cluster 0 : Bank Visitors

  • Average credit limit is low to medium for majority of the customers
  • Prefer to often visit bank for transactions
  • Rarely visit online for transactions.

Cluster 1 : Phone Call Users

  • Low credit limit compared to other clusters.
  • Total credit cards is the low amonth all the clusters
  • Average online transactions.
  • High number of calls to bank

Cluster 2 : Digital Users

  • Customers in this cluster has the higest average credit limit among all the clusters
  • Customers in this cluster have high number of credit cards among all the clusters
  • Often do online transactions

Business Recommendations¶

  • Cluster 0 Customers - Often visit bank for transactions. Banks should promote online usage among these customers.
  • Cluster 1 Customers - They have low credit limit and also have less number of credit cards. Bank should provide higher credit limit to these customers. Also improve phone customer services.
